post_cb({"10817071": {"ParentId": "10816564", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2012-05-30T13:14:56.847", "OwnerUserId": "1211392", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "10817071", "Score": "1", "Body": "<p>In the C++ SPEC(eg:N3337) say:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10816564_10817071_0\">3 The keyword static can be used to declare a local variable with static storage duraion.</p>\n<p id=\"so_10816564_10817071_1\">(Page: 62; section 3.7.1 Static storage duration)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In your case, the variable <code>static bool sameName</code> is belong to the scope of the function <code>fun</code>. And the other variable <code>static bool sameName</code> is belong to the scope of the function <code>moreFun</code>. These two static variables belong to different scope. The <code>static</code> keyword effect to duration only, it's not effect scope.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-05-30T13:14:56.847"}, "10816564": {"CommentCount": "0", "ViewCount": "982", "PostTypeId": "1", "ClosedDate": "2012-06-22T12:01:59.483", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "CreationDate": "2012-05-30T12:43:26.797", "LastActivityDate": "2012-05-31T05:38:22.837", "Title": "Same name for a static variable within a static member function", "AcceptedAnswerId": "10816633", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:04:53.537", "Id": "10816564", "Score": "1", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_10816564_10816564_0\"><strong>Possible Duplicate:</strong><br>\n<a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2756940/how-are-static-variables-with-the-same-name-in-different-functions-identified-by\">How are static variables with the same name in different functions identified by the System?</a> </br></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>How does compiler make the difference between two local static variables that have the same name, but are defined in two different (static) member functions? </p>\n<pre><code>class Type\n{\n    public:\n        static void fun()\n        {\n            static bool sameName = false;\n\n            // work with sameName\n\n        }\n        static void moreFun()\n        {\n            static bool sameName = false;\n\n            // work with sameName\n        }\n};\n</code></pre>\n", "Tags": "<c++><static>", "OwnerUserId": "704028", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_10816564_10817071_0": {"section_id": 7166, "quality": 0.8, "length": 8}}, "n3337": {"so_10816564_10817071_0": {"section_id": 6910, "quality": 0.8, "length": 8}}, "n4659": {"so_10816564_10817071_0": {"section_id": 8674, "quality": 0.8, "length": 8}}}, "10816633": {"ParentId": "10816564", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "3", "CreationDate": "2012-05-30T12:47:42.133", "Score": "4", "LastEditorUserId": "45685", "LastEditDate": "2012-05-31T05:38:22.837", "Id": "10816633", "OwnerUserId": "45685", "Body": "<p>it has to do with scope.</p>\n<p>the sameName exists in two different scopes / in this case two function scopes</p>\n<p>so internally the variables maybe are referred to with names fun.sameName and moreFun.sameName (names just arbtitrary invented by me but show the principle).</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2012-05-31T05:38:22.837"}});